!! Module shape

```
title: $:/plugins/rimir/mindmap-elixir/adapter.js
type: application/javascript
module-type: mindmapengine
```

Exports a constructor function (`module.exports = Engine`). The host widget calls `new Engine(wiki)` for each `<$mindmap>` instance. Function `name` is overridden to `MindElixir` via `Object.defineProperty` so the host's name-based discovery matches.

!! Library bundling

```
lib/mind-elixir.umd.js     (mind-elixir IIFE + CommonJS shim; module-type: library)
lib/mind-elixir.css        (mind-elixir stylesheet; $:/tags/Stylesheet)
```

The mind-elixir distribution ships an IIFE form (`MindElixir.iife.js`) which assigns `var MindElixir = (function(W){...})({})` inside the script body. We append a CommonJS export line so it works through TW's `require()` machinery:

```js
if (typeof module !== "undefined" && module.exports) { module.exports = MindElixir; }
```

!! MDOM ↔ mind-elixir mapping

|!MDOM |!mind-elixir |
|`id` |`id` (unchanged) |
|`label` |`topic` (icon prefix appended when `core:icon` is set) |
|`body` |`note` |
|`attrs["core:color"]` |`style.background` |
|`attrs["core:collapsed"]` |`expanded: false` |
|`attrs["mx:tags"]` |`tags` |
|`attrs["mx:hyperLink"]` |`hyperLink` |
|`crossLinks` |`linkData` (preserved, not yet rendered) |

Nodes with `attrs["core:hidden"] === true` are filtered out at the boundary; they don't appear in mind-elixir at all.

!! Operation translation

mind-elixir emits `operation` events via `me.bus.addListener("operation", fn)`. Each is translated into a single Op object and emitted to the host widget via `on("op", ...)`:

|!mind-elixir |!Op |
|`finishEdit` |`rename` |
|`removeNode` |`removeNode` |
|`addChild` |`addNode` (parent = `op.origin.id`) |
|`moveNode` / `moveNodeBefore` / `moveNodeAfter` |`reparent` |
|other |`setAttr` `mx:lastOp` (round-trip preserve) |

!! Capabilities

```
{ applyOps: false, focus: true, expand: true, drag: true, edit: true }
```

`applyOps = false` in v1 — the widget always calls `engine.update(mdom)` after any change. mind-elixir's `refresh(data)` is used internally so this is reasonably cheap; promoting `applyOps` to `true` is a v2 optimisation.

